## Invariants (read before acting)

- **Identity is ALWAYS `{{ email_address }}`.** Every read, draft, send
  acts as {{ email_address }}. You never speak as anyone else.
- **Free-form replies ALWAYS go through the engine** via `cs draft-reply
  "…"`, which composes with memory + trained voice + threading and stores a
  DRAFT. **Never** a cs-SMTP path, never a draft written from scratch in cs,
  never `cs chat --allow` (the operator's supervised send path, not yours —
  and denied to you by permission).
- **You only ever DRAFT — you cannot send.** `cs draft-reply` has no send
  capability, and the headless permission set forbids every send surface.
  Going autonomous-send later is a deliberate permission change the operator
  makes, not a flag this skill flips. Don't look for a way to send — there
  isn't one, by design.
- **DEFAULT ON UNCERTAINTY = ESCALATE.** Never auto-send a free-form
  reply. In draft mode every reply is a draft the operator approves; a
  judgment call gets left for the operator, not answered.
- **NEVER invent facts.** Use only what is in the thread + engine memory.
  If the answer is not grounded there → ESCALATE, do not guess.
- **"Have we already replied to X?" = the SENT ARCHIVE, across threads.**
  This is the dedup truth (CLAUDE.md). The authoritative check is: is there a
  {{ email_address }} message SENT to that contact AFTER their inbound — `cs contacted
  <email>`, which now reads **Gmail's Sent folder directly**
  (`cs/gmail_archive.py`), the real ground truth. Do NOT use the engine's
  `emails.search folder:sent` for this: it misses mail sent by hand from
  Gmail. **Check across threads, not within one** — the reply/
  confirmation very often lives in a SIBLING thread (different subject), so
  reading the one thread the customer wrote in misses it. Neither a single
  `emails.list_by_thread` read NOR a vague `cs ask` question is reliable for
  this binary: both have answered it WRONG (a per-thread read missed a
  sibling-thread confirmation; the engine chat called two answered threads
  "unanswered"). The Sent archive does not lie.
- **Engine memory/tasks are for CONTEXT and judgment, not the binary.** Use
  `cs ask` / `cs tasks` to understand a situation and to surface forwards —
  but before flagging anything "unanswered / urgent", CONFIRM against the Sent
  archive. Raw thread read is ONLY for pulling exact text to ground a draft.

## 1. Find what genuinely still needs a human answer

**PRIMARY candidate source (deterministic):** `cs unanswered --days 14 --json`.
It enumerates every inbound of the last 14 days (Gmail All Mail, Date-header
windowed) and subtracts every sender {{ accounts_default }}@ has since written to (Gmail Sent =
dedup ground truth), returning only senders with NO reply after their last
message, oldest-first. This **replaced** an LLM `cs ask` discovery query that was
NON-DETERMINISTIC — two runs of the same query returned different sets and missed
real unanswered client mail 6–13 days old that had no engine task (incident
2026-07-16, Privacar/Bonometto pre-sales 10 Jul plus four others 3–10 Jul).

```bash
.venv/bin/python -m cs unanswered --days 14 --json    # PRIMARY — deterministic Sent-anchored sweep
.venv/bin/python -m cs tasks --json                   # SECONDARY signal (engine may create NO task for a real inbound)
```

`cs unanswered` does NOT classify intent — it can over-include autoresponders and
system/no-reply senders (unless they are listed in `CS_SYSTEM_SENDERS`); filter
those with judgment. It also cannot see mail **Mario FORWARDED** to {{ accounts_default }}@ (the
`Fwd:` sender is Mario, a SELF address, so it is excluded): for those keep the
`cs tasks` signal and treat a `Fwd:` / `from:mario.alemi` with NO {{ accounts_default }}@ reply
to the ORIGINAL sender as a real catch.

Then for EACH candidate, the authoritative unanswered-check — across threads:

```bash
.venv/bin/python -m cs contacted <email>     # or: emails.search to:<email> folder:sent
```

- If {{ email_address }} already sent a message to that contact AFTER their inbound →
  **ANSWERED. Drop it.** Do not flag, do not draft. (This is where the bad
  report went wrong: it flagged Bistrot + MADEA as urgent-open when {{ email_address }}
  had already replied — MADEA's confirmation was in a sibling thread.)
- Only what survives the Sent-archive check is genuinely open. (Forwarded mail
  with NO {{ email_address }} reply to the original sender is the real catch — e.g. a
  `Fwd:` from Mario where nobody answered the customer.)

## 1b. Reconcile each survivor against the engine task ledger

The Sent-anchored sweep only sees {{ accounts_default }}@'s OWN Sent folder. It CANNOT see a
reply Mario sent from his personal mailbox (`mario.alemi@…`) — so an item
handled elsewhere still surfaces (incident 2026-07-17: Eva Fani was answered
from `mario.alemi@` personal; the sweep re-flagged it). The engine task ledger
is where we record that a contact is handled, so for every survivor, match by
`contact_email` against the ledger and apply this rule:

```bash
.venv/bin/python -m cs tasks --json                                  # OPEN tasks
.venv/bin/python -m cs rpc tasks.list '{"include_completed":true}'   # includes CLOSED (cs tasks --json = OPEN only)
```

- **OPEN task for that contact** → work it (draft / escalate as below).
- **CLOSED (completed) task for that mail** → **SKIP** — already handled
  (possibly answered from another mailbox / a personal account the Sent sweep
  can't see). This is the fix for "handled elsewhere but the sweep still flags
  it".
- **NO task at all** → the engine's own detection missed it; create one so the
  desktop sees it, then work it:

```bash
.venv/bin/python -m cs tasks create --email <email> --title "<breve>" \
  --event-id <message-id> [--thread-id <tid>] [--urgency high] [--reason "<perché>"]
```

- When the operator (or Mario) says an item is handled → close it:

```bash
.venv/bin/python -m cs tasks close <task_id> --note "<come/dove risolto>"
```

## 2. Pull exact text ONLY to ground a draft

For a candidate that survived the Sent-archive check (genuinely unanswered)
AND you intend to draft, read the real bodies to ground the reply in the
customer's exact words:

```bash
.venv/bin/python -m cs rpc emails.list_by_thread '{"thread_id":"<thread_id>"}'
```

⚠️ Returns **`{"emails":[…]}`** (a dict). Read **bodies**, not the snippet
(snippets often show {{ email_address }}'s own autoresponder). Use this for CONTENT —
the wording you reply to — never to decide handled-state (step 1 settled
that via the engine).

## 2b. When unsure HOW to answer — search past mail, don't guess

If you are not fully sure how to answer (a mechanic like credits/top-up, a
policy, what we previously promised, how we phrase it): **memory first** (this
skill + `cs ask`), and **if memory is thin → SEARCH {{ email_address }}'s PAST SENT MAIL
for precedent**, then ground the reply in how we actually handled it before:

```bash
.venv/bin/python -m cs rpc emails.search '{"query":"<termini>","folder":"sent","limit":8}'
.venv/bin/python -m cs rpc emails.list_by_thread '{"thread_id":"<id>"}'   # read the real wording
```

NEVER invent mechanics, prices, steps, or commitments — lift them from the past
emails (or escalate if you can't find them). **After you draft, UPDATE memory**
with what you learned, so next time it's already there. (Doing the opposite —
guessing instead of searching the archive — is the Styven/Fani mistake.)

## 3. Decide per candidate

For each candidate the engine flagged open, decide. Two outcomes only:

**(a) Answerable within {{ email_address }}'s normal scope** — a question about
{{ company_display_name }}, a routine account/config issue, a normal reply where the answer
is **grounded in the thread + engine memory**:

```bash
.venv/bin/python -m cs draft-reply "rispondi nel thread con <email>: <cosa dire, conciso>"
```

`draft-reply` runs the engine compose (memory + trained voice + threading
headers `In-Reply-To`/`References`) and stores a **DRAFT** in {{ email_address }}/Bozze
for the operator to review and send. It has **no `--allow` option and cannot
send** — the engine denies `send_draft` whatever the message (or any injected
text) says. Sending is the operator's job (review the Gmail draft, send from
there); autonomous-send is a future, separately-permissioned step, **never
this skill's job**.

**(b) Escalate** — a judgment call, out of scope, legal- or
billing-sensitive, angry, an unclear ask, OR an answer you cannot ground
in the thread + memory → **do NOT auto-answer**. Leave the engine task
**open** (do not mark it handled) and list it for the operator in the
report. **When in doubt, this branch.**

## 4. Idempotency — do not re-draft on the next tick

A 2h re-run must NOT draft a second reply to a thread you already drafted.
The handled-signal comes from the ENGINE, not a raw thread re-read:
- Step 1 already asked the engine for what is STILL unanswered — a thread you
  drafted last tick should no longer surface (a draft now exists in it). Trust
  that: work only what step 1 returns as open.
- A drafted thread that still surfaces (the draft isn't a "reply" yet) is
  guarded by checking, via the engine, whether an unsent {{ email_address }} DRAFT
  already exists for that contact (`cs ask "c'è già una bozza per <email>?"`
  or the engine's draft list) — if yes, skip; do not draft a duplicate.
- Escalations are deliberately NOT drafted/closed — they resurface until the
  operator deals with them.

## 5. Honour the safety gates throughout

- {{ email_address }} identity is never dropped.
- Every free-form reply goes through the engine (`cs draft-reply`), never cs-SMTP.
- Everything is a DRAFT (`cs draft-reply`); nothing is sent — by design and
  by permission. The operator approves and sends.
- Uncertain / out-of-scope / sensitive / ungrounded ⇒ ESCALATE.
- If a step fails (daemon down, RPC error), capture a one-line note and
  continue; surface it under `Note:` in the report rather than guessing.

## 6. Report

Now — and only now — report to the operator. Italian, founders'
register: tight, complete sentences, no jargon, no emoji, no "fammi
sapere". Compact and skimmable:

```
triage-support-mail — <n> candidati

Bozze pronte (da rivedere e inviare):
- <email> — "<oggetto>"
- …

Escalation (servono te):
- <email> — "<oggetto>" — <motivo: fuori scope / dubbio / sensibile / non fondato>
- …

Note: <una riga per nota; ometti se nessuna>
```

Omit a section if it is empty. The report is the only place this skill
speaks; everything above it is silent.

